      <p>
        Matplotlib has a module called <em>animation</em> that uses 
        frames of a changing graph to create gif and mp4 files.
        First, however, we will need to learn about for loops and user-defined functions 
        to efficiently repeat and reuse code.<fn>Animation
            is basically a slideshow of pictures or frames.</fn> 
      </p>

      <subsection>
        <title>Repeating blocks of code with for loops</title>
        <p> 
          A for loop repeats a block of code for each item in a list or array. 
          The code below uses a for loop to add elements to an array one at a time. 
        </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            import numpy as np

            list = [] #create an empty Python list

            for i in np.linspace(0,5,6): #for each number in this array
                list.append(i) #append to our list

            print(np.array(list)) #print list with appended values

            for tval in np.linspace(0,2*np.pi, 5):
                list.append(tval)

            print(np.array(list)) #print list with additional appended values
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p>
          Note that we converted the Python list into a Numpy array before printing. 
          NumPy also has an append function that effectively recreates the entire array before appending
          which is inefficient in a for loop. 
        </p>
